Nice and readable — it does the job. A few friendly suggestions to make it clearer, safer and a bit more idiomatic:

- Use the += operator for brevity:
  total += arr[i];

- Prefer modern constructs when appropriate:
  - for...of is clearer when you only need the values:
    for (const value of arr) total += value;
  - Or use reduce for a functional one-liner:
    const total = arr.reduce((sum, v) => sum + v, 0);

- Make sure total is initialized and scoped correctly (let/const) so you’re not accidentally using a global:
  let total = 0;

- Consider input safety: if arr can contain non-numeric values you may want to coerce or filter them (e.g., Number(v) or Number.isFinite checks) to avoid unexpected concatenation or NaN.

- Micro-optimization note: caching arr.length (const len = arr.length) was common in old engines but modern JS engines optimize this, so it’s usually unnecessary.

Example (concise and clear):
let total = 0;
for (const value of arr) total += value;

Or:
const total = arr.reduce((sum, v) => sum + v, 0);

Overall your loop is fine — these are just small stylistic/safety tweaks.
